After Froben’s death Erasmus felt responsibility for his godson (Lond. xxviii. 1, LB. 1084, 125111), and had him at Freiburg in the autumn of 1529. In Oct. the boy’s guardians recalled him 1ο go to Paris (Basle MS. D. IV. 18. 309 v0, 311 v⁰); but were persuaded to send him to Groclen at Louvain (Lond. xxvi. 51, LB. 1079: Q. pp, 59-61). He was there in Aug. 1530, but in Nov. 1531 was at Lille, learning French (Basle MS. Goclenii Epist. ff. 6, 9) ; Erasmus' offer to take the boy for the summer of 1531, and advice to make him a scriniarius (Horawitz ii. 9) being both declined. By Nov. 1534 he had returned to Basle (Basle MS. D. IV. 18. 444 ; cf. Q. p. 45). On 23 Aug. 1536 (BRE. 296, 300) he married Katharine Weckhart; and then joined his stepfather, John Herwagen, in the printing business, vols. 3 and 4 of the Basle Galen, 1538, and the Paroemiae of Apostolius, 1538, being from their press. In Jan. 1542 lie divorced his wife for adultery with Hei-wagen3 and by Feb. 1545 appears to have married again. See Heitz and Bernoulli, Basler Biichermarken‚ 1895, pp. xx, xxvii, xxx.
